      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Creatine does not stop working as long as you continue taking it. Once muscle saturation is achieved (3-4 weeks at 3-5g daily), the benefits remain stable for as long as supplementation continues. If you stop taking creatine, muscle stores deplete over 4-6 weeks and benefits gradually fade. There is no tolerance development or diminishing returns from long-term use — the 5-year safety and efficacy studies show sustained benefits without need for cycling.' },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'Should women take creatine pictures to track progress?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Yes, weekly progress photos are far more useful than scale weight for tracking creatine effectiveness in women. Take front, side, and back photos in consistent lighting, posture, and clothing every 1-2 weeks. Scale weight will increase 1-3 pounds from water retention, which can be misleading without visual context. Most women see meaningful visible changes by week 6-8, and dramatic changes by month 3-4 when combined with consistent resistance training.' },
