    <!-- COMMON MISTAKES -->
    <h2>Common Mistakes That Sabotage Creatine Results</h2>

    <div class="warn-box">
      <span class="warn-box-ico">&#9888;</span>
      <p><strong>Avoid these common mistakes that prevent women from seeing the full creatine before-and-after potential:</strong></p>
      <ul style="margin:12px 0 0 0;padding-left:20px;">
        <li><strong>Quitting at week 2 because of water weight.</strong> Trust the process — the scale is misleading early on. Photos and gym performance are the truthful metrics.</li>
        <li><strong>Skipping rest days.</strong> Muscle saturation requires daily dosing. Skipping days slows the timeline by weeks.</li>
        <li><strong>Underdosing.</strong> 1-2g per day is sub-clinical. Take 3-5g daily for full benefits.</li>
        <li><strong>Choosing low-quality products.</strong> Underdosed or contaminated creatine produces no results. Insist on third-party testing.</li>
        <li><strong>Not training progressively.</strong> Creatine amplifies training adaptation — without progressive overload, there is little to amplify.</li>
        <li><strong>Inadequate protein intake.</strong> Lean mass cannot accumulate without sufficient amino acid raw materials.</li>
        <li><strong>Cycling on and off.</strong> Cycling reverses progress every 4-6 weeks. Long-term studies show no benefit to cycling — take it continuously.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <!-- VERDICT -->
    <div class="verdict">
      <h3>Our Verdict: Realistic Expectations Lead to Real Results</h3>
      <p><strong>The realistic creatine before-and-after for women is more measured than Instagram suggests but more impactful than skeptics claim.</strong> Within 2-4 weeks: visible muscle fullness and early performance gains. Within 8-12 weeks: meaningful strength improvements and visible body composition changes (combined with training). Within 3-6 months: substantial functional and aesthetic results that compound over time.</p>
      <p>The women who see the most dramatic before-and-afters share four traits: consistent daily dosing (including rest days), progressive resistance training 3-4x weekly, adequate protein intake (0.8-1g per pound bodyweight), and patience to let the timeline play out. The women who quit at week 2 because the scale rose 2 pounds never see what creatine can actually do.</p>
      <p>Take photos, track strength progress, ignore the scale, and commit to 12 weeks. The before-and-after results are worth it.</p>
    </div>

